<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the 1:300 attic ventilation rule?", answer: "IRC section R806.2 allows attic ventilation at 1 square foot of net free area (NFA) per 300 square feet of attic floor, provided that at least 40 percent and no more than 50 percent of the ventilation is high (ridge, gable, or roof vents) and the rest is low (soffit or eave vents), and the ceiling has a vapor retarder. For an 1,800 sq ft attic, that means 6 sq ft of NFA total — 3 sq ft intake at the soffit and 3 sq ft exhaust at the ridge. If you cannot balance the vents 50/50, fall back to 1:150." },
  { question: "What is Net Free Area (NFA)?", answer: "NFA is the actual open area of a vent through which air can flow, excluding the frame, screen, and louvers that block air. Vent manufacturers publish NFA on their product labels — a typical 8×16 inch soffit vent might have a gross area of 128 sq in but a NFA of only 65 sq in because screens and louvers block the rest. Always use NFA (not gross area) when calculating ventilation." },
  { question: "How many soffit vents do I need?", answer: "Divide the required intake NFA by the NFA of each vent. If you need 432 sq in of intake NFA and each soffit vent has 65 sq in NFA, you need 7 vents. Distribute them evenly along the soffit — a vent at each rafter bay is ideal if your soffit material allows. Continuous strip soffit vents are easier to install and provide consistent airflow; the strip-type rating is usually 9 sq in NFA per linear foot." },
  { question: "Why does attic ventilation matter?", answer: "Proper attic ventilation removes summer heat that bakes shingles and raises cooling bills, and removes winter moisture that condenses on cold sheathing, causing mold and rot. It also prevents ice dams by keeping the attic air temperature close to outdoor temperature so snow melts evenly instead of refreezing at the eaves. An under-ventilated attic is the #1 cause of premature shingle failure and of winter ice dam damage to ceilings." },
  { question: "Can I use only a ridge vent?", answer: "No — a ridge vent without adequate soffit intake creates a negative pressure that can pull conditioned air from the living space, defeating the point. Ventilation requires balanced intake and exhaust. If you cannot add soffit vents (blocked soffits, boxed cornices), use gable vents or low roof vents instead. The total intake NFA should roughly match the exhaust NFA." }
]) %>

